# **Lesson 3 Tasks: Text-Level Elements, Images, and Hyperlinks**

## **Setup Instructions**

Before starting these exercises:
1. Create a new folder called `html-lesson3` on your computer
2. Create a subfolder called `images` inside it
3. Open your text editor
4. Save each exercise as a separate `.html` file
5. For image exercises, you can use placeholder images or create simple text files named as images

---

## **Task 1: Text-Level Elements Practice**

**Objective:** Use various text-level elements to mark up content.

**Instructions:**
1. Create a file called `text-elements.html`
2. Create a page about a book or movie with:
   - A heading with the title
   - A paragraph using `<em>` for emphasis
   - A paragraph using `<strong>` for importance
   - The title of the work using `<cite>`
   - A quote using `<q>`
   - At least one abbreviation using `<abbr>` with a `title` attribute

**Example Structure:**
```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <meta charset="utf-8" />
    <title>Book Review</title>
</head>
<body>
    <h1>Review: [Book Title]</h1>
    
    <p>
        This book is <em>absolutely</em> worth reading. 
        The most <strong>important</strong> message is...
    </p>
    
    <p>
        <cite><!-- Book title here --></cite> was written by...
    </p>
    
    <!-- Add more paragraphs with other elements -->
</body>
</html>
```

**Success Criteria:**
- Uses at least 5 different text-level elements
- Elements are used appropriately (semantic meaning)
- Abbreviations have title attributes
- Page displays correctly with proper formatting

---

## **Task 2: Scientific Document**

**Objective:** Use subscript, superscript, and code elements.

**Instructions:**
1. Create a file called `science.html`
2. Create a science reference page with:
   - A heading "Chemical Formulas and Equations"
   - A paragraph about water using H<sub>2</sub>O
   - A paragraph about Einstein's equation E = mc<sup>2</sup>
   - A section showing how to write HTML code using `<code>` elements
   - Use character entities to display the HTML tags

**Example:**
```html
<section>
    <h2>Water</h2>
    <p>
        The chemical formula for water is H<sub>2</sub>O.
    </p>
</section>

<section>
    <h2>HTML Code</h2>
    <p>
        To create a paragraph, use the <code>&lt;p&gt;</code> tag.
    </p>
</section>
```

**Requirements:**
- At least 3 uses of subscript
- At least 3 uses of superscript
- At least 5 code examples showing HTML tags
- All HTML symbols properly escaped with entities

**Success Criteria:**
- Subscripts and superscripts display correctly
- Code examples are readable
- Character entities work properly

---

## **Task 3: Character Entities**

**Objective:** Practice using character entities for special symbols.

**Instructions:**
1. Create a file called `symbols.html`
2. Create a page that uses these character entities:
   - Copyright symbol (&copy;)
   - Trademark symbol (&trade;)
   - Registered symbol (&reg;)
   - Em dash (&mdash;)
   - En dash (&ndash;)
   - Less than and greater than (&lt;, &gt;)
   - Quote marks (&quot;)
   - Euro symbol (&euro;)

**Example Section:**
```html
<section>
    <h2>Company Information</h2>
    <p>
        TechCorp&reg; &copy; 2025<br />
        Our ThinkPad&trade; is the best in class.
    </p>
</section>

<section>
    <h2>Pricing</h2>
    <p>
        Prices range from &euro;50&ndash;&euro;150
    </p>
</section>
```

**Success Criteria:**
- Uses at least 8 different character entities
- Entities display correctly as symbols
- Appropriate use in context

---

## **Task 4: Line Breaks and Addresses**

**Objective:** Use line breaks appropriately.

**Instructions:**
1. Create a file called `contact-card.html`
2. Create a business card style page with:
   - Company name
   - Address (use `<br />` for line breaks)
   - Phone number with proper formatting
   - Email address
   - A short tagline

**Example:**
```html
<section>
    <h2>Contact Information</h2>
    <p>
        <strong>Acme Corporation</strong><br />
        123 Business Street<br />
        Suite 456<br />
        New York, NY 10001
    </p>
    
    <p>
        Phone: 212-555-0123<br />
        Email: info@acme.com
    </p>
</section>
```

**Requirements:**
- At least 3 uses of `<br />`
- Formatted address
- Use `<strong>` for company name
- Use en-dash for phone number formatting

**Success Criteria:**
- Information displays on separate lines
- Professional formatting
- Proper use of text-level elements

---

## **Task 5: First Image**

**Objective:** Insert an inline image with proper attributes.

**Instructions:**
1. Create a file called `first-image.html`
2. Find or create an image file and save it in the `images` folder
3. Create a page with:
   - A heading
   - A paragraph
   - An image using `<img>` with:
     - `src` pointing to your image
     - Descriptive `alt` text
     - `width` and `height` attributes

**Example:**
```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <meta charset="utf-8" />
    <title>My First Image</title>
</head>
<body>
    <h1>Welcome to My Page</h1>
    
    <p>Check out this image:</p>
    
    <img src="images/photo.jpg" 
         alt="Descriptive text about the image" 
         width="400" 
         height="300" />
    
    <p>Description of the image...</p>
</body>
</html>
```

**Success Criteria:**
- Image displays in browser
- Alt text is descriptive and meaningful
- Width and height are specified
- Image path is correct

---

## **Task 6: Image Gallery with Figures**

**Objective:** Create an image gallery using `<figure>` and `<figcaption>`.

**Instructions:**
1. Create a file called `gallery.html`
2. Create a photo gallery page with:
   - A main heading "Photo Gallery"
   - At least 3 `<figure>` elements, each containing:
     - An `<img>` tag
     - A `<figcaption>` with a description

**Template:**
```html
<main>
    <h1>Photo Gallery</h1>
    
    <section>
        <figure>
            <img src="images/photo1.jpg" 
                 alt="Description of photo 1" 
                 width="300" 
                 height="200" />
            <figcaption>Caption for photo 1</figcaption>
        </figure>
        
        <!-- Add more figures -->
    </section>
</main>
```

**Requirements:**
- Minimum of 3 figures
- Each image has meaningful alt text
- Each caption describes the image
- Semantic structure (use sections if organizing by theme)

**Success Criteria:**
- Images display with captions below them
- Alt text and captions are different but complementary
- Proper HTML structure

---

## **Task 7: Basic Links**

**Objective:** Create internal navigation links.

**Instructions:**
1. Create THREE files: `home.html`, `about.html`, `contact.html`
2. In each file, create:
   - A header with site name
   - Navigation with links to all three pages
   - Main content area with unique content for each page
   - Footer

**home.html Navigation Example:**
```html
<nav>
    <ul>
        <li><a href="home.html">Home</a></li>
        <li><a href="about.html">About</a></li>
        <li><a href="contact.html">Contact</a></li>
    </ul>
</nav>
```

**Requirements:**
- All three pages link to each other
- Links work when clicked
- Consistent navigation on all pages
- Each page has different content

**Success Criteria:**
- Can navigate between all pages by clicking links
- Links change color when clicked (browser default)
- No broken links

---

## **Task 8: Link Variations**

**Objective:** Practice different types of links.

**Instructions:**
1. Create a file called `link-types.html`
2. Create a page demonstrating:

**External link (opens in new tab):**
```html
<a href="https://www.example.com" target="_blank">External Website</a>
```

**Link with title attribute:**
```html
<a href="page.html" title="Click to learn more">Learn More</a>
```

**Link to page section:**
```html
<!-- Create a section with id -->
<section id="contact">
    <h2>Contact Us</h2>
</section>

<!-- Link to that section -->
<a href="#contact">Jump to Contact</a>
```

**Download link:**
```html
<a href="document.pdf" download>Download PDF</a>
```

**Requirements:**
- At least one of each link type
- External link opens in new tab
- Section link jumps to correct location
- Title attributes provide helpful information

**Success Criteria:**
- All link types work correctly
- External links open in new tabs
- Anchor links scroll to sections
- Download attribute works (create a dummy file)

---

## **Task 9: Email and Phone Links**

**Objective:** Create clickable email and phone links.

**Instructions:**
1. Create a file called `contact-links.html`
2. Create a contact page with:

**Email link:**
```html
<p>
    Email us at: 
    <a href="mailto:info@company.com">info@company.com</a>
</p>
```

**Email with subject:**
```html
<p>
    <a href="mailto:support@company.com?subject=Support Request">
        Contact Support
    </a>
</p>
```

**Phone link:**
```html
<p>
    Call us: 
    <a href="tel:+15555551234">(555) 555-1234</a>
</p>
```

**SMS link:**
```html
<p>
    <a href="sms:+15555551234">Text Us</a>
</p>
```

**Requirements:**
- At least 2 email links (one with subject)
- At least 2 phone links
- At least 1 SMS link
- Proper formatting of phone numbers

**Success Criteria:**
- Email links open email client
- Subject pre-fills in email
- Phone links work on mobile
- SMS links open messaging app

---

## **Task 10: Image as Link**

**Objective:** Make images clickable.

**Instructions:**
1. Create a file called `image-links.html`
2. Create a page with:
   - A logo image that links to home page
   - Three thumbnail images that link to different pages
   - Each image wrapped in an `<a>` tag

**Example:**
```html
<header>
    <a href="home.html">
        <img src="images/logo.png" alt="Company Logo" width="200" height="100" />
    </a>
</header>

<section>
    <h2>Our Services</h2>
    
    <a href="service1.html">
        <img src="images/service1.jpg" alt="Web Design Services" width="200" height="150" />
    </a>
    
    <!-- More image links -->
</section>
```

**Requirements:**
- Logo links to home
- At least 3 clickable images
- Alt text describes each image
- Images are properly sized

**Success Criteria:**
- Clicking images navigates to correct pages
- Alt text is descriptive
- No broken images or links

---

## **Task 11: Complete Restaurant Website**

**Objective:** Build a multi-page restaurant website with all learned elements.

**Instructions:**

Create a restaurant website with FOUR pages:

### **1. index.html (Home Page)**
```html
<header>
    <a href="index.html">
        <img src="images/logo.png" alt="Restaurant Logo" />
    </a>
    <h1>Restaurant Name</h1>
</header>

<nav>
    <!-- Links to all 4 pages -->
</nav>

<main>
    <section>
        <h2>Welcome</h2>
        <figure>
            <img src="images/restaurant.jpg" alt="Restaurant interior" />
            <figcaption>Our cozy dining room</figcaption>
        </figure>
        <p>Welcome message with <em>emphasized</em> and <strong>important</strong> text.</p>
    </section>
    
    <section>
        <h2>Featured Dishes</h2>
        <!-- 3 dishes with images as links to menu page -->
    </section>
</main>

<footer>
    <p>&copy; 2025 Restaurant Name</p>
</footer>
```

### **2. menu.html (Menu Page)**
- Navigation (consistent with home)
- At least 3 sections (Appetizers, Entrees, Desserts)
- Each section has:
  - Heading
  - Unordered list of items
  - Prices using proper en-dash
  - At least 2 images with figures

### **3. about.html (About Page)**
- Navigation
- "Our Story" section with 2-3 paragraphs
- "Meet the Chef" section with:
  - Image of chef
  - Biography with proper text-level elements
- "Hours" section with description list

### **4. contact.html (Contact Page)**
- Navigation
- Contact form introduction
- Contact information:
  - Address with line breaks
  - Clickable phone number
  - Clickable email address
  - SMS link
- Map or location image
- Link to each section of page from top

**Requirements Checklist:**
- [ ] 4 complete, linked pages
- [ ] Consistent navigation on all pages
- [ ] At least 8 images total across all pages
- [ ] Uses `<figure>` and `<figcaption>` at least 3 times
- [ ] Email link with subject
- [ ] Phone link in international format
- [ ] SMS link
- [ ] At least 5 different text-level elements used
- [ ] At least 5 character entities used
- [ ] Image links (clickable images)
- [ ] Section links (jump to page sections)
- [ ] External link (review site, social media)
- [ ] Proper semantic HTML throughout

**Success Criteria:**
- All pages accessible from navigation
- All links work correctly
- Images display properly with alt text
- Contact links functional
- Professional appearance
- Valid HTML structure

